that correct and give nuance to global and imperial histories. The result of a collaborative research process involving Indigenous and non-Indigenous contributors, this book looks closely at the circumstances of making, use, and circulation of these objects: things that supported and defined both Indigenous resistance and colonial and imperial purposes. Contributors re-envision the histories of northern North America by focusing on the lives of things flowing to and from this vast region between the eighteenth and the twentieth centuries, showing how material culture is a critical link that tied this diverse landscape to the wider world. An original perspective on the history of northern North American peoples grounded in things, Object Lives and Global Histories in Northern North America provides a key analytical and methodological lens that exposes the complexity of cultural encounters and connections between local and global communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural relationsxHistoryvCase studies. 0aIndigenous artxMaterial culturezCanadaxHistoryvCase studies. 0aIndigenous art. 0aIndigenous peoplesxMaterial culturezCanadaxHistoryvCase studies. 0aIndigenous peoples-Material culture. 7aART / Native American.2bisacsh1 aBerry, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertram, Laurie K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalf, Judy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomarnisky, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLainey, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat